        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>March 12<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental">Dallas</seg>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I do not know whether your many corrections ever allow you now to bring out translations, or whether, if you have the time, you would think it worth while to translate the life of my G. F. in the accompanying number of Kosmos.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    <p>My brother &amp; self think the sketch interesting &amp; we wish to publish it as a separate very little book in honour of our grandfather.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> In case you would undertake it, we sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> wish you to correct the proofs &amp; that your name sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> appear on the title page as translator, for this w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> guarantee to everyone that it has been faithfully done. I wd endeavour to get Murray to publish it on commission, for I suppose only a few copies w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be sold.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> state that I have written to E. Krause for permission, &amp; cannot doubt that this I shall receive.—<ref target="#foot.f5"/> After looking at the article, will you kindly inform me what compensation w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. make it worth while for you to undertake the work soon. If you are not willing to translate it can you tell us of anyone, though I have no doubt I c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> easily find out from <hi rend="italic">[6 words illeg]</hi></p>
<p>very truly C. D.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 ever] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.1 now] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n3">1.2 whether] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n4">1.2 the] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n5">1.2 you would] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘whether’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n6">2.2 in … grandfather] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n7">2.2 we] <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘I’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n8">2.3 to … your] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n9">2.3 name sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>] ‘sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>’ <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘to’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n10">2.3 on … page] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n11">2.4 for this w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>] <hi rend="italic">interl after del</hi> ‘as a’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n12">2.5 wd endeavour to get] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. [<hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘get’]’; ‘wd’ <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n13">2.5 for] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘though’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n14">2.5 I] <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘we’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n15">2.5 few] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘very’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n16">2.7 this] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n17">2.7 After] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘It occurs to us at first that perhaps M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Murray w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> turn out the life together with’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n18">3.1 very] <hi rend="italic">after del illeg</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11935.xml">letter from W. S. Dallas, 14 March 1879</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In addition to his position as assistant secretary  to the Geological Society of London, Dallas was also editor of <hi rend="italic">Annals and Magazine of Natural History</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Popular Science Review</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Geological Magazine</hi> n.s. decade 3, vol. 7 (1890): 335). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2758.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ernst Krause</ref> had published ‘<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1219.xml">Erasmus Darwin</ref>, der Großvater und Vorkämpfer <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Darwin’s</ref>: ein Beitrag zur Geschichte der Descendenz-Theorie’ (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1219.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Erasmus Darwin</ref>, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Darwin’s</ref> grandfather and forerunner: a contribution to the history of descent theory; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10668.xml">Krause 1879a</ref>) in <hi rend="italic">Kosmos</hi> in February 1879.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1211.xml">Erasmus Alvey Darwin</ref> had suggested that a translation of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10668.xml">Krause 1879as</ref> would make an interesting book (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11918.xml">letter from E. A. Darwin, 8 March [1879]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2575.xml">John Murray</ref> was CD’s publisher. With books published on commission, all publication expenses were paid by the author; CD’s other books were published under a profit-sharing model in which the publisher paid the initial cost of printing and advertising and these expenses were repaid from sales.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11920.xml">letter to Ernst Krause, 9 March 1879</ref>. Krause gave his permission for a translation to be made in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11925.xml">letter of 12 March 1879</ref>.</note>
        </div>
    
